    "headline": "Youngest Children Face the Longest Waits for Kindergarten Spots",
    "lede": "For many families, getting a spot in kindergarten is a big worry—especially for the youngest kids. The numbers show that children aged 12 to 17 months face the longest waiting lists in Reykjavík, with as many as 25 in line in some neighborhoods. Meanwhile, older toddlers often wait far less, making age a key factor in how long families must wait.",
    "story_blocks": [
      {
        "type": "callout",
        "body": "In some districts, as many as 25 of the youngest children are waiting for a kindergarten spot.",
        "highlight_value": "25",
        "highlight_label": "children waiting (age 12–17 months)"
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Big Gaps in Waiting Lists by Age Group",
        "body": "In the chart below, you can see the number of children on kindergarten waiting lists across different age groups. It's immediately clear that the youngest group—those just 12 to 17 months old—face the biggest wait, while older age groups see much smaller numbers. The gap between the youngest and next oldest is large, showing how much tougher it is for parents with babies to secure a place.",
        "viz_index": 0
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "Youngest and Oldest: Who Waits the Most?",
        "body": "The second chart highlights the extremes: the age group with the most children waiting (12–17 months) and the one with the fewest (18–23 months). This makes it easy to spot just how wide the difference is—only one toddler in the 18–23 month group is waiting in some places, compared to up to 25 among the youngest. Most other age groups fall somewhere in between.",
        "viz_index": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "narrative",
        "heading": "What This Means for Parents and Kids",
        "body": "For families with very young children, the waiting game is longest. This can mean extra months of juggling child care or changing work plans. For older toddlers, the path to kindergarten is a bit smoother. If you're planning ahead for your own family, age might make all the difference."
      }
    ],
    "data_note": "These numbers show how many children in Reykjavík are waiting for a kindergarten spot, broken down by age group and district. The data comes from several parts of the city but doesn't specify totals for each neighborhood—all focus is on age groups. The most recent update is from April 2026. Some details about the data's permissions were not available, so check with the city if you need official usage rights.",
    "followup_question": "How many children are enrolled in kindergartens across the city each year?",
